description:
Another dark nebula housing a cluster of young stars burning bright and blue.  A lot like the Iris Nebula,  which I'm working on concurrently, but with more blue reflection than most LDNs.  

I haven't run across this much on Astrobin.  Not sure why as the surrounding dark nebulousity is lovely and the nearby star cluster adds something too.  

I was away at the Oregon Star Party for three nights with no internet whatsoever.  That meant I had to set the remote rig on "Loop" with CCDAutopilot - something I never do.  Luckily, it worked.  The only issue was that the command to raise the CCD temprature during the day did not trigger.  So the camera stayed on at 100% for days.  

Searching for more info on this after I completed it, I found an APOD of this a year or two ago.  That showed an SNR in Ha too.  So I guess I'll start the Ha capture tonight...

EDIT: After a full night of 30 minute Ha subs not a trace of the SNR was seen.  I went back to the APOD and saw that this data came from the Subaru telescope.  OK, moving on now...
title: NGC 7129 The Small Cluster Nebula
